🔹 Step 1
Open Kali Linux in VirtualBox.
🔹 Step 2
Open Terminal.
🔹 Step 3: Start Local HTTP Server
Run:
python3 -m http.server 8080
This starts a local web server on port 8080.
You should see output like:
Serving HTTP on 0.0.0.0 port 8080 ...
🔹 Step 4: Start Packet Capture
Open a new terminal window and run:
sudo tcpdump -i any -w capture.pcap port 8080
Explanation:
-i any → capture on all interfaces
-w capture.pcap → save packets to file
port 8080 → capture only HTTP traffic on port 8080
🔹 Step 5: Generate Traffic
Open Firefox in Kali Linux and go to:
http://localhost:8080
Refresh the page multiple times to generate traffic.
🔹 Step 6: Stop Capture
Go back to the tcpdump terminal.
Press:
Ctrl + C
It will stop capturing and display number of packets captured.
The file capture.pcap is now saved.
🔹 Step 7: Locate Capture File
Click Kali Dragon icon (top-left)
Open File Manager
Open Home folder
Locate capture.pcap
🔹 Step 8: Open in Wireshark
Double-click capture.pcap.
It opens directly in:
4
Wireshark for analysis.
🔹 Step 9: Filter Login Packets
In Wireshark filter bar, type:
http.request.method == "POST"
Press Enter.
Now only HTTP POST packets are shown.
🔹 Step 10: Analyze Packet Details
Click on any HTTP packet.
You will observe:
Browser information (User-Agent)
Operating System
Browser version
Language
Requested URLs
If form submitted → username & password in plain text

This proves that HTTP is insecure.
